We're facing an issue with authorization mode "allow all" and some manifests that uses RBAC resources.

As far as we understood, the RBAC API is enabled by default but not the RBAC authorizer (<https://github.com/kubernetes/features/issues/2#issuecomment-330569468>).

So a manifest using RBAC resources should works (RBAC API would create unused stuff as there is not the RBAC authorizer to use them).

But we get a message "<http://clusterroles.rbac.authorization.k8s.io|clusterroles.rbac.authorization.k8s.io> "xxx" is forbidden: attempt to grant extra privileges" like there is an authorizer doing its authorization job (but we're yet using the flag `--authorization-mode=AlwaysAllow`).

Does one have an idea about it ? do we miss something ? or is that some kind of bug with authz system ?

Taking issue <https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/issues/56022> here
Most notably option #2 that is being pushed here: <https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/pull/56659>

Option 2 states that Devices can be re-used between InitContainers and regular containers. However:
- If a device is re-used, no allocate calls are issued before making the device available again in the subsequent containers
- You have no control on what device gets re-used for what container

IMHO this solution is completely off topic.
It basically describes a weak sharing mechanism with no control on what device gets re-used for what container.

This goes against the current device plugin architecture assumption that devices are exclusives.
I also expect devices to always be in the same state as long as we have exclusive usage.

Finally we don't support Device sharing therefore it seems strange that we are implementing a device sharing mechanism for the 1.9 release almost on a whim, without really discussing it in any meeting.

Device Sharing is a major feature and is not an easy challenge. It seems weird that we are not even discussing it in a meeting.

I noticed on the Statefulset doc ```"Before a scaling operation is applied to a Pod, all of its predecessors must be Running and Ready."```

Now that means that if a zone is down and hosts the beginning of the sequence (pod-0, pod1), then we cannot scale anymore or self heal. If pod-15 dies, it won't be re-created because pod-0 is down. Pod-0 won't start because it's bound to the Zone in which the volume was created (volumes are zone specific).

That seems silly.  I've detailed this issue here with Cassandra example: <https://github.com/kubernetes/examples/issues/149>
